7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">The capacity case ha</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">now been </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">articulated with</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">evidence on the experience for passengers of crowding, congestion  and punctuality on the West Coast Main Line</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">The economic case continues to use cautious assumptions, which if replaced by more realistic assumptions on growth continuing into the longer term results in ‘very hi</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">gh’</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> value for money estimates</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">here is now clear evidence that HS2 will strengthen northern and Midland economies more than those of the south and London.</span></li></ul></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">Greengauge 21 is a not-for-</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">profit company established to promote the debate on high-speed rail for Great Britain.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">The recently updated Strategic Case for HS2 answers its many critics.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> It shows the business case to be ‘high’ – indeed ‘very high’ if the likelihood of demand continuing to grow into the longer term is taken into account.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">There were several areas where consultants employed by campaign group 51M argued the previous analysis of HS2 was flawed or made use of out-dated assumptions.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> These technical assumptions have now been updated or addressed (see Table 1). </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Table 1 ‘Fundamental Weaknesses’ in the earlier HS2 economic appraisals</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="color:#4f81bd; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:37.1pt; width:375.55pt"><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#1f497d; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.75pt; border-right-color:#1f497d; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.75pt; border-top-color:#808080; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.75pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical